Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Trim the @courgette{1}. Create long ribbons by running a #peeler{} down the
courgette lengthways.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Roughly chop the @parsley{5%g} (stalks and all).

Place a large pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the onion and garlic until fragrant, stirring occasionally,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @chopped tomatoes{1%pack}, @creme fraiche{110%g}, @balsamic vinegar{1%sachet}
and half the @Italian herbs{1/2%sachet} (double for 4p).

Stir well and season with @sugar{1/2%tsp} (double for 4p), @salt{to taste} and
@pepper{to taste}.

Cook on low heat for ~{5%minutes}.

> Loosen the sauce with a splash of water if it becomes too thick.

Lay the courgette ribbons out flat, side by side, in the bottom of an
#oven dish{} (don't worry if they overlap a little).

Drain and tear the @mozzarella{125%g} into small pieces.

Pour the sauce from the pan over the courgette ribbons.

Arrange the mozzarella pieces on top.

Season with salt and pepper.

Bake in the oven until mozzarella is melted, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, boil a large #pot{} of salted @water{to taste} for the rigatoni.

When boiling, add the @dried rigatoni{180%g} to the water and bring back to
the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with oil and stir through to prevent sticking.

> If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Stir half the chopped parsley into the drained rigatoni.

Season with salt and pepper and toss to combine.

Divide the pasta between #bowls{} or #deep plates{} and spoon the courgette and
creamy sauce over the top.

Garnish with the remaining parsley.